text: We can grossly divide the ethics market into the listed market, which is a fairly small segment of the ethics market. And that market is on the CME, and you have a few CTAs there, but the volumes are not really meaningful. We constantly read that commitment of trade report, and then they say, well, dollar volumes or dollar positioning is to the roof. Everybody's long dollar, and that's partially true, but that's only because they are trend following. So if dollar moves higher, then it makes sense that their position will be maximum. But I wouldn't read too much into that, despite what people think. The part that's really moving the market is the OTC market. When you see that on Twitter, that not too many retail accounts really understand that market and know that market. And the reason is that the barriers of entry are pretty high. So. To have an access to the ethics for market on the OTC market, you really need to have either ethics prime brokerage account, which is quite expensive and requires a lot of margin. All you need to have is the master. As a retail trader, you can't have either one of them unless you put a lot of margin, which the other traders don't have. And I think that this market can be grossly divided into three groups. So the first group would be the sales side. And the sales side would have the dealers like a lot of swap dealers, investment banks, second tier banks. They have known dealer market makers. So that's a small segment within that group. But I think it's a growing one because I just read that Optiver, which is a market maker across multiple assets, started to gain more traction and is currently showing prices on multi dealer platforms. So I think that in that sense, it's a growing player. In that segment. And then you have the interbank brokers like Tradition and GFI that basically just broker between dealers. So that would be the sales side. On the buy side, you have the corporate and the hedgers and the real money that basically come to that market just to hedge their ethics exposure, their cash flows and their long and short term cross currency funding needs. They provide most of the sales. They supply and demand to the market. And they are volume sensitive. So in a way, they need to hedge whether or not volume is at 10, 15 or 20 because they have exposure and they need to hedge that away. They create a lot of those dislocations that volume managers try to offset or to outtrudge. Then the other group on the buy side would be the macro managers that take directional views on the FX market. They think the dollar is going to go to 150, 160. Then they will buy calls. They will do some structuring. They will do some structures to enjoy that move. And you have multi-managers who are trying to use FX as part of their own books. So they diversify into FX either in VOR or in other types of strategy. And the last subset of speculative account would be the relative value or the FX board managers. And they are kind of a secondary risk underwriter. So they will try to take advantage of dislocation created by the macro managers and by the corporates. And the dealers don't want to warehouse that risk or don't have the capacity of just trying to take advantage of VOR. And they are very sensitive to VOR. So that would be the FX option market.
